Our homes’ most underrated feature? Interior glazed doors (doors with glass).

Frosted or clear, full lite or half lite, glazed doors are just a little more special than your standard door. We’ve used them for bathrooms (frosted, naturally!), laundry rooms and craft rooms. Swipe to see.

Why would you want to use a glazed door instead of a solid door?

💡to bring in light from other parts of the home. This makes them especially ideal for windowless rooms

🎭 to create connection but still afford privacy. Looking through the glass, you can observe what’s happening on the other side without actually disturbing the scene.

💫 to add a dash of the unexpected and bring personality to your home

👉🏼 for directional purposes. Paired with signage (I have a thing for vinyl lettering), they are a clever and stylish way to distinguish which door is which

Would you use glazed doors in your home? I think they would be great for home offices, pantries, and home gyms too.

We hadn’t planned on going to Europe. But when we discovered we had enough air miles in our account and Sean’s work trip to Antwerp coincided with the week of March break, we had to make it happen. 🛫

👇 6 budget room decorating tips 💫

1️⃣ Use what you have. Move and reuse decor from room to room. 

In this room I’ve reused a Pottery Barn Kids peg rail, desk, and large scale art that hung in our previous home. Don’t hesitate to hold onto classic, well-made pieces that can fit in any room.

2️⃣ Paint the room a new colour scheme.

3️⃣ Plan your layout before you buy.

Switching your living room from summer☀️ to fall🍂 is easy. Just a few simple changes can bring instant coziness:

1/ Light a candle 🕯️

From tall tapers to faux flickering pillars, candlelight brings a restful feeling. Place in a hurricane for added drama.

2/ Add textured pillows 

Trade your cotton pillow covers for ones with texture and weight. They make any seat more inviting.

3/ Wrap a sofa seat in a wool throw 🛋️

Give your sofa a new look for the season with the addition of a plaid throw. Wrapped around the seat cushions, it creates a cozy spot to sit with a book or to enjoy the fire.

4/ Use a woven tray

A wicker, seagrass or rattan tray can add warmth to your coffee table display. Use it to corral a pleasing arrangement of books, florals, and interesting objects.

5/ Bring in nature 

Take a step outdoors for acorns, branches, or cuttings from the garden. Placed in a bowl or small pitcher, they lend an organic touch to any surface.

There’s Instagram clean and then there’s Reality clean. And that’s ok.

This closet hides all the things that don’t have a permanent home and items I haven’t been able to part with. Like seasonal candles I’ve only used half way, the bedtime books I used to read Chloe every night, and eight copies of the book Sean and I wrote in 2007. You know, the stuff of life.

I’ve become less nostalgic about things. I realize our ownership of objects is temporary, fleeting. One day they hold immense meaning and the next, they’re a relic that takes up space and causes us stress.

So you hold onto the memory and let go of the object. Pass the goods on to someone else who can still make use out of them.

Cleaning clutter is a way of making room for new memories. Today? I’m clearing space for great things to come.
